declarations.comments:
Takes a `Parser Char` and matches it zero or more times, returning
a `String` of what was matched.
declarations.title: many

declarations.comments:
Takes a `Parser Char` and matches it one or more times, returning
a `String` of what was matched.
declarations.title: many1

declarations.comments:
The `char` parser constructor returns a parser which matches only the
specified single character.
declarations.title: char

declarations.comments:
The `notChar` parser constructor makes a parser which will match any
single character other than the one provided.
declarations.title: notChar

declarations.comments: Matches any one character from the provided string.
declarations.title: oneOf

declarations.comments: Matches a single digit.
declarations.title: digit

declarations.comments: Matches a single whitespace character.
declarations.title: space

declarations.comments: Matches a single letter, digit or underscore character.
declarations.title: alphanum

declarations.comments: Matches a single ASCII letter.
declarations.title: letter

declarations.comments: Matches a single upper case ASCII letter.
declarations.title: upper

declarations.comments: Matches a single lower case ASCII letter.
declarations.title: lower

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't a digit.
declarations.title: notDigit

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't whitespace.
declarations.title: notSpace

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't a letter, digit or underscore.
declarations.title: notAlphanum

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't an ASCII letter.
declarations.title: notLetter

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't an upper case ASCII letter.
declarations.title: notUpper

declarations.comments: Matches a single character which isn't a lower case ASCII letter.
declarations.title: notLower

declarations.comments: Run a parse operation on a stream.
declarations.title: parse

declarations.comments:
The `succeed` parser constructor creates a parser which will simply
return the value provided as its argument, without consuming any input.

This is equivalent to the monadic `return`.
declarations.title: succeed

declarations.comments: The `fail` parser will just fail immediately without consuming any input.
declarations.title: fail

declarations.comments:
The `failAt` parser will fail immediately without consuming any input,
but will report the failure at the provided input position.
declarations.title: failAt

declarations.comments:
A parser combinator which returns the provided parser unchanged, except
that if it fails, the provided error message will be returned in the
`ParseError`.
declarations.title: expected

declarations.comments:
The `item` parser consumes a single character, regardless of what it is,
and returns it as its result.
declarations.title: item

declarations.comments:
The `cut` parser combinator takes a parser and produces a new parser for
which all errors are fatal, causing `either` to stop trying further
parsers and return immediately with a fatal error.
declarations.title: cut

declarations.comments:
Takes two parsers `p1` and `p2`, returning a parser which will match
`p1` first, discard the result, then either match `p2` or produce a fatal
error.
declarations.title: cutWith

declarations.comments:
The `seq` combinator takes a parser, and a function which will receive
the result of that parser if it succeeds, and which should return another
parser, which will be run immediately after the initial parser. In this
way, you can join parsers together in a sequence, producing more complex
parsers.

This is equivalent to the monadic `bind` operation.
declarations.title: seq

declarations.comments:
The `either` combinator takes two parsers, runs the first on the input
stream, and if that fails, it will backtrack and attempt the second
parser on the same input. Basically, try parser 1, then try parser 2.

If the first parser fails with an error flagged as fatal (see `cut`),
the second parser will not be attempted.

This is equivalent to the `alt` operation of `MonadPlus`/`Alt`.
declarations.title: either

declarations.comments:
Converts a parser into one which will return the point in the stream where
it started parsing in addition to its parsed value.

Useful if you want to keep track of where in the input stream a parsed
token came from.
declarations.title: withStart

declarations.comments:
The `sat` parser constructor takes a predicate function, and will consume
a single character if calling that predicate function with the character
as its argument returns `true`. If it returns `false`, the parser will
fail.
declarations.title: sat

declarations.comments:
The `maybe` parser combinator creates a parser which will run the provided
parser on the input, and if it fails, it will returns the empty value (as
defined by `mempty`) as a result, without consuming any input.
declarations.title: maybe

declarations.comments: Matches the end of the stream.
declarations.title: eof

declarations.comments:
The `many` combinator takes a parser, and returns a new parser which will
run the parser repeatedly on the input stream until it fails, returning
a list of the result values of each parse operation as its result, or the
empty list if the parser never succeeded.

Read that as "match this parser zero or more times and give me a list of
the results."
declarations.title: many

declarations.comments:
The `many1` combinator is just like the `many` combinator, except it
requires its wrapped parser to match at least once. The resulting list is
thus guaranteed to contain at least one value.
declarations.title: many1

declarations.comments:
Matches the provided parser `p` zero or more times, but requires the
parser `sep` to match once in between each match of `p`. In other words,
use `sep` to match separator characters in between matches of `p`.
declarations.title: sepBy

declarations.comments:
Like `sepBy`, but cut on the separator, so that matching a `sep` not
followed by a `p` will cause a fatal error.
declarations.title: sepByCut

declarations.comments:
Matches the given parser zero or more times, returning a string of the
entire match.
declarations.title: many

declarations.comments:
Matches the given parser one or more times, returning a string of the
entire match.
declarations.title: many1

declarations.comments: Turns a parser of `Char` into a parser of `String`.
declarations.title: fromChar

declarations.comments: Matches the exact `Char` provided, returning it as a string.
declarations.title: char

declarations.comments: Matches any one character except the one provided, returning a string.
declarations.title: notChar

declarations.comments: Matches the exact string provided.
declarations.title: string

declarations.comments: Matches zero or more whitespace characters.
declarations.title: spaces

declarations.comments: Matches one or more whitespace characters.
declarations.title: spaces1

declarations.comments: Matches zero or more non-whitespace characters.
declarations.title: notSpaces

declarations.comments: Matches one or more non-whitespace characters.
declarations.title: notSpaces1

declarations.comments: Parses a positive or negative integer.
declarations.title: int

declarations.comments: Parses a positive or negative floating point number.
declarations.title: float

declarations.comments:
Parses a double quoted string, with support for escaping double quotes
insite it, and returns the inner string. Does not perform any other form
of string escaping.
declarations.title: quotedString
